    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Stationary measure for the open KPZ equation
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Corwin%2C+I">Ivan Corwin</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Knizel%2C+A">Alisa Knizel</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12253v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;with general inhomogeneous <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann</span> boundary conditions at $0$ and $1$ depending on real parameters $u$ and $v$, respectively. When $u+v\geq 0$ we uniquely characterize the constructed stationary measures through their multipoint Laplace transform which we prove is given in terms of a stochastic process that we call the continuous dual Hahn process.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12253v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.12253v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.12253v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        We provide the first construction of stationary measures for the open KPZ equation on the spatial interval $[0,1]$ with general inhomogeneous <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann</span> boundary conditions at $0$ and $1$ depending on real parameters $u$ and $v$, respectively. When $u+v\geq 0$ we uniquely characterize the constructed stationary measures through their multipoint Laplace transform which we prove is given in terms of a stochastic process that we call the continuous dual Hahn process.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.12253v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.12253v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

