    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Randomness extraction in computability theory
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Cenzer%2C+D">Douglas Cenzer</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Porter%2C+C+P">Christopher P. Porter</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.03971v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;notions of randomness with respect to different underlying probability measures. We analyze several classes of extraction procedures: a first class that generalizes von <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann&#39;s</span> trick for extracting unbiased randomness from the tosses of a biased coin, a second class based on work of generating biased randomness from unbiased randomness by Knuth and Yao&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.03971v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.03971v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.03971v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        In this article, we study a notion of the extraction rate of Turing functionals that translate between notions of randomness with respect to different underlying probability measures. We analyze several classes of extraction procedures: a first class that generalizes von <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann&#39;s</span> trick for extracting unbiased randomness from the tosses of a biased coin, a second class based on work of generating biased randomness from unbiased randomness by Knuth and Yao, and a third class independently developed by Levin and Kautz that generalizes the data compression technique of arithmetic coding. For the first two classes of extraction procedures, we identify a level of algorithmic randomness for an input that guarantees that we attain the extraction rate along that input, while for the third class, we calculate the rate attained along sufficiently random input sequences.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.03971v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.03971v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 5 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    

    

    
  </li>

