    <p class="title is-5 mathjax">
      
        Boundedness in a fully parabolic attraction-repulsion chemotaxis system with nonlinear diffusion and singular sensitivity
      
    </p>
    <p class="authors">
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Authors:</span>
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Chiyo%2C+Y">Yutaro Chiyo</a>, 
      
      <a href="/search/?searchtype=author&amp;query=Yokota%2C+T">Tomomi Yokota</a>
      
    </p>
    
    <p class="abstract mathjax">
      <span class="search-hit">Abstract</span>:
      <span class="abstract-short has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.02246v1-abstract-short" style="display: inline;">
        &hellip;-\nabla \cdot (G(u)χ(v)\nabla v)
  +\nabla\cdot(H(u)ξ(w)\nabla w), \quad
  v_t=d_1Δv+αu-βv, \quad
  w_t=d_2Δw+γu-δw, \quad
  x \in Ω,\ t&gt;0, \end{align*} under homogeneous <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann</span> boundary conditions and initial conditions, where $Ω\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ $(n \ge 1)$ is a bounded domain with smooth boundary, $d_1, d_2, α, β, γ, δ&gt;0$ are constants. Also,&hellip;
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.02246v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'inline'; document.getElementById('2103.02246v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'none';">&#9661; More</a>
      </span>
      <span class="abstract-full has-text-grey-dark mathjax" id="2103.02246v1-abstract-full" style="display: none;">
        This paper deals with the quasilinear fully parabolic attraction-repulsion chemotaxis system \begin{align*}
  u_t=\nabla \cdot (D(u)\nabla u)
  -\nabla \cdot (G(u)χ(v)\nabla v)
  +\nabla\cdot(H(u)ξ(w)\nabla w), \quad
  v_t=d_1Δv+αu-βv, \quad
  w_t=d_2Δw+γu-δw, \quad
  x \in Ω,\ t&gt;0, \end{align*} under homogeneous <span class="search-hit mathjax">Neumann</span> boundary conditions and initial conditions, where $Ω\subset \mathbb{R}^n$ $(n \ge 1)$ is a bounded domain with smooth boundary, $d_1, d_2, α, β, γ, δ&gt;0$ are constants. Also, the diffusivity $D$, the density-dependent sensitivities $G, H$ fulfill $D(s)=a_0(s+1)^{m-1}$ with $a_0&gt;0$ and $m \in \mathbb{R}$; $0 \le G(s) \le b_0(s+1)^{q-1}$ with $b_0&gt;0$ and $q&lt;\min\{2,\ m+1\}$; $0 \le H(s) \le c_0(s+1)^{r-1}$ with $c_0&gt;0$ and $r&lt;\min\{2,\ m+1\}$, and the signal-dependent sensitivities $χ, ξ$ satisfy $0&lt;χ(s)\le \frac{χ_0}{s^{k_1}}$ with $χ_0&gt;0$ and $k_1&gt;1$; $0&lt;ξ(s)\le \frac{ξ_0}{s^{k_2}}$ with $ξ_0&gt;0$ and $k_2&gt;1$. Global existence and boundedness in the case that $w=0$ were proved by Ding (J. Math. Anal. Appl.; 2018;461;1260-1270) and Jia-Yang (J. Math. Anal. Appl.; 2019;475;139-153). However, there has been no work on the above fully parabolic attraction-repulsion chemotaxis system with nonlinear diffusion and singular sensitivity. This paper develops global existence and boundedness of classical solutions to the above system by introducing a new test function.
        <a class="is-size-7" style="white-space: nowrap;" onclick="document.getElementById('2103.02246v1-abstract-full').style.display = 'none'; document.getElementById('2103.02246v1-abstract-short').style.display = 'inline';">&#9651; Less</a>
      </span>
    </p>
    

    <p class="is-size-7"><span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">Submitted</span> 3 March, 2021; 
      <span class="has-text-black-bis has-text-weight-semibold">originally announced</span> March 2021.
      
    </p>
    

    
